FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "NIS2 supply-chain clauses turn large operators' approved-vendor lists into a security-certification gate the pre-launch entrant cannot pass in Year 1",
 "narrative": "The venture's declared first channel is large operators — the cust.operator-large node at 0.40, itself an unsourced internal estimate. But large CE data-center operators are essential entities under NIS2 (transposing across CE through 2024–26, Germany via the NIS2 implementation act), and Article 21(2)(d) obliges them to manage ICT supply-chain risk. Operationally this arrives as supplier-security questionnaires demanding ISO/IEC 27001 and IEC 62443 evidence for any networked device that touches their management plane — which an intelligent PDU does by definition. A pre-launch entrant holds none of these artifacts. The law never names PDU vendors, so it appears on no vendor risk list; it closes the primary channel anyway, forcing deals through OEM/integrator wrappers at lower margin and slower pace.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "NIS2 transposition makes large DC operators essential entities with legally-mandated supply-chain security duties; procurement operationalizes this as mandatory supplier security certifications (ISO 27001, IEC 62443-4-1/-4-2) for networked equipment on the management network — the category an intelligent PDU sits in",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Product",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c12"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The 0.40 buyer-mix estimate rests on capacity shares and qualitative channel logic with no evidence of how much large-operator spend sits behind certified approved-vendor lists; a pre-launch entrant with no certification history fails AVL onboarding regardless of product quality, and the sales motion migrates to OEM/integrators whose certifications wrap the product",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "ledger:cust.oem",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The large-operator slice reachable by this entrant in Year 1 is materially smaller than the modeled 0.40 — the funnel's largest buyer node overstates the addressable channel for precisely the venture's chosen entry path",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "NIS2 regulates operators, not vendors — a vendor-side regulatory checklist never surfaces it. It arrives disguised as a procurement questionnaire, not a law, and by the time the first AVL rejection lands, two quarters of the 12-month window are gone.",
 "falsifier": "Supplier-onboarding documentation from ≥2 large CE operators showing networked rack-power vendors are admitted on self-declaration, without ISO 27001/IEC 62443 certification prerequisites.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Large regulated buyers historically translate their own compliance duties into supplier certification requirements (finance, telecom, energy all followed this pattern); NIS2's supply-chain article makes DC operators the next instance. Uncertainty is the share of spend behind hard gates versus soft questionnaires. [evidence revision: The regulatory trigger is fully confirmed (NIS2 in force in Germany; Art. 21(2)(d) supply-chain duties; questionnaires demanding ISO 27001). But the one concrete large-operator onboarding artifact found (STACK) presents supplier qualification as a self-declaration questionnaire, not a binary certification gate — suggesting the 'cannot pass in Year 1' outcome is likely for some but not all large operators. This is consistent with the original base-rate estimate; slight downward nudge reflects direct evidence that questionnaire-based onboarding admits non-certified vendors on declaration in at least some cases.]"
}

